<html>
  <head>
    <title> Example Website </title>
  </head>
<body>
  <h1> Main Heading </h1>
    <p> This text is the introduction to the rest of the page. If the page is a long one it might be split up into several sub-headings. </p>
  <h2> Sub-Heading </h2> 
    <p> Long articles have sub-headings to help follow structure to being written. </p>
  <h2> Another Sub-Heading </h2> //interesting, noticing that h2 is the same code for the second heading, but it is all dependent on the size of the heading
    <p> Here you can see another sub-heading </p>
</body> 
</html>


//the html code <> are called elements: usually made up of two tags
//1. opening tag - opening to begin
//2. closing tag - closing tag has an extra forward slash in it.
// The character in the brackets indicate the tag's purpose and the closing tag has a fowrad slash after the < symbol
// Before the <body> element, there is the <head> element that contains information about the page. This title is 
// shown in the top of the browser.
// <p> </p> - p stands for paragraph, 
// an element comprises the opening tag and the closing tag and the content lies between them.
// Attributes are in the opening tag of the element and have a name and a value seperated by an equal sign.
// < p lang = "en-us"> Paragraph in English </p>
// The attribute name indicates what kind of extra information you are supplying about the element's content in lowercase.
// The value is the information for teh attribute in double quotes. 
// This example indicuates the language used in this element which is US English.
